<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1911-10-16T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1911-10-16T00:00:00-05:00" n="261" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d261">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 893.00/579.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Chargé d’Affaires at
                                    St. Petersburg</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi>.</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">St. Petersburg</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1911-10-16">
                                    <hi rend="italic">October 16, 1911</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>Your October 14. Neratoff informs me that reports from affected districts
                            are most disquieting, Russia has no missionaries there and few business
                            men at safe points. He thinks, however, concentration of all foreigners
                            at accessible ports highly desirable. In his opinion situation at
                            present does not call for further measures by the powers.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Wheeler.</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>